"In some cases I've noticed that it's impossible to get them off their phones for anything, even when they have to get off," said Márkó, who started cutting hair 30 years ago. "There's no discipline."

So, starting this year, Márkó announced to clients and gift givers that his haircuts would be free. But in return, he asks that customers or parents hand their phones to the stylists, at least for the hours that they are in the salon. Márkó and the 16 other hair stylists at his business willingly follow the no-phone policy.

The Lombárdj Irodai Notebooks, a Rádió 1 interview with Ponytail Joe:

The idea was well received, and many new clients are now coming in because their kids usually don't get their haircut without their phone.

"I see that more and more is done by new generations via mobile phone," Márkó continued. "They don't know any other way of communicating. Even kids seven, eight, or ten years old are among those whose parents say have to be at a certain place. From what I can see, parents are quite distracted."
